Title:
Depths of Windows APC – Aspects of internals of the Asynchronous Procedure Calls from the kernel mode

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This post is a deep dive into Windows Asynchronous Procedure Calls (APCs) with emphasis on kernel-mode internals and how user-mode APC delivery is orchestrated by the kernel/ntdll boundary. It explains key kernel structures (KAPC, KAPC_STATE, KTHREAD) and nuances like APC environments when threads are attached to other processes (KeStackAttachProcess / KeUnstackDetachProcess). The author highlights common kernel APC pitfalls (NonPagedPool allocation requirements, IRQL/critical-region blocking behavior, and RundownRoutine semantics) and a practical driver-unload hazard where queued APC callbacks can execute after a driver is unloaded, proposing a JMP-based ObfDereferenceObject pattern as a workaround. For user-mode APCs, it details delivery mechanics via KiDeliverApc/KiInitializeUserApc and ntdll!KiUserApcDispatcher, plus forcing delivery with NtTestAlert/NtContinue. It includes injection-related case studies: early DLL injection hazards (kernel32 not initialized; prefer ntdll!LdrLoadDll and minimal imports), PsSetLoadImageNotifyRoutine timing gotchas, and a QueueUserAPC vs ZwQueueApcThread comparison including an activation-context bug that can crash/corrupt remote processes. It also covers advanced cross-bitness APC techniques (RtlQueueApcWow64Thread / PsWrapApcWow64Thread) and a module-enumeration method using remote APC + shared section, with notes on CFG export suppression and SetProcessValidCallTargets.

Technical Focus:
- Windows kernel APC internals (KAPC/KAPC_STATE/KTHREAD, KiInsertQueueApc)
- Thread attach/detach APC environments (KeStackAttachProcess, ApcStateIndex/SavedApcState)
- IRQL, critical regions, and APC blocking (KeEnterCriticalRegion, APC_LEVEL, special APCs)
- User-mode APC delivery path (KiDeliverApc, KiInitializeUserApc, ntdll!KiUserApcDispatcher, NtTestAlert/NtContinue)
- APC-based injection timing pitfalls (kernel32/loader state, PsSetLoadImageNotifyRoutine)
- Cross-process/cross-bitness APC queuing and mitigations (ZwQueueApcThread vs QueueUserAPC, activation context bug, WOW64 APC, CFG export suppression)

Use Cases:
- Kernel driver developers avoiding APC-related BSODs (pool type, IRQL, rundown handling)
- Building/assessing APC-based DLL injection (including “early” injection constraints and loader-state issues)
- Remote thread/APC execution primitives using native APIs (ZwQueueApcThread, RtlCreateUserThread)
- Cross-bitness operations in WOW64 targets (queueing 64-bit and 32-bit APCs appropriately)
- Remote module enumeration via shared sections + LdrQueryProcessModuleInformation
- Debugging/forensics of crashes caused by APC timing, activation contexts, or driver unload races

Keywords:
Windows APC, KAPC, KAPC_STATE, KTHREAD, KeInitializeApc, KeInsertQueueApc, KiDeliverApc, KiInitializeUserApc, KiUserApcDispatcher, KeStackAttachProcess, KeUnstackDetachProcess, NonPagedPool, IRQL, APC_LEVEL, KeEnterCriticalRegion, RundownRoutine, PsSetLoadImageNotifyRoutine, ZwQueueApcThread, QueueUserAPC, activation context, RtlDispatchAPC, RtlQueueApcWow64Thread, PsWrapApcWow64Thread, LdrLoadDll, NtTestAlert, NtContinue, CFG export suppression, SetProcessValidCallTargets